# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antinatalism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] Estimated and projected populations of the world and its continents (except Antarctica) from 1950.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] The shaded regions correspond to the range of projections by the United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] The Day of Seven Billion, October 31, 2011, is the day that has been officially designated by the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) as the approximate day on which the total world population reached a population of seven billion people.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon spoke at the United Nations building in New York City on this milestone in the size of world population about the issues that it will raise, along with promoting 7 Billion Actions.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] The 7 Billion Actions Campaign aims to raise awareness of key population issues such as reproductive health, poverty, women empowerment, youth, environment sustainability, ageing, and urbanization, by encouraging people to take action and recommit to humanity.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] The campaign will count and showcase 7 billion online and offline actions that tell the story of the people behind the number and the connections they share with each other and the issues they each face.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] The 7 Billion Actions Campaign centers on highlighting individuals and organizations making a significant impact and creating innovative solutions in the 7 key issues identified as most imperative for the growing global population.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] 7BillionActions.org: Showcases stories, interviews, and news.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] In-depth platform to help individuals connect and take action with efforts taking place near them or across the globe.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] Interactive data visualizations highlighting challenges and solutions.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] I Count: An online and SMS/mobile effort allowing anyone on Earth to step forward to be counted as one of the 7 billion and share what issues matters most to them.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] These are but a few of the important resources being created to facilitate connection and collaboration.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] World Story Book: A community-created collection of photos, text, audio, and video that tell the stories of struggle and success of the people behind the number.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] 7Billion Hashtag (#7Billion): An ongoing social media conversation on Twitter, Facebook, and other major social media platforms (representing each major region) designed to help fuel awareness, engagement, and participation.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] IBM: As a way to celebrate its 100th anniversary, IBM is launching its Global Celebration of Service, a worldwide volunteer service initiative which calls for staff to donate their time and energy to specific social causes.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] 7 Billion Actions will be presented as one of the official programs which staff can support.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] As part of the new partnership, IBM volunteers will contribute their engineering, marketing, communications, social media and analytics expertise to help build the 7 Billion Actions campaign platform.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] crowdSPRING: crowdSPRING launched a series of design competitions to crowd source the official logo for the 7 Billion Actions Campaign.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] The first round of the competition drew over one thousand submissions and the winning design will become the 7 Billion Action Campaign's official global logo.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] The next phase will open voting to the public in order to select a group of regionally themed logos.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] Blog Talk Radio: Using their telephone-to-internet platform, the 7 Billion Actions Campaign will launch the Conversations for a World at 7 Billion channel to showcase a variety of audio programs discussing the topics and themes facing the 7 billion.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] People in different countries and regions will have the opportunity listen to and call into these programs and share their stories and actions.
[src:antinatalism/7-billion-actions] Playing for Change: The non-profit group the Playing for Change Foundation will partner with 7 Billion Actions to produce an official campaign song.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:antinatalism/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Various components of the absurd are discussed in the academic literature, and different theorists frequently concentrate their definition and research on different components.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] On the practical level, the conflict underlying the absurd is characterized by the individual's struggle to find meaning in a meaningless world.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The theoretical component, on the other hand, emphasizes more the epistemic inability of reason to penetrate and understand reality.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Traditionally, the conflict is characterized as a collision between an internal component of human nature, and an external component of the universe.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] However, some later theorists have suggested that both components may be internal: the capacity to see through the arbitrariness of any ultimate purpose, on the one hand, and the incapacity to stop caring about such purposes, on the other hand.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Certain accounts also involve a metacognitive component by holding that an awareness of the conflict is necessary for the absurd to arise.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some arguments in favor of absurdism focus on the human insignificance in the universe, on the role of death, or on the implausibility or irrationality of positing an ultimate purpose.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Objections to absurdism often contend that life is in fact meaningful or point out certain problematic consequences or inconsistencies of absurdism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Defenders of absurdism often complain that it does not receive the attention of professional philosophers that it merits in virtue of the topic's importance and its potential psychological impact on the affected individuals in the form of existential crises.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Various possible responses to deal with absurdism and its impact have been suggested.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The three responses discussed in the traditional absurdist literature are suicide, religious belief in a higher purpose, and rebellion against the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Of these, rebellion is usually presented as the recommended response since, unlike the other two responses, it does not escape the absurd and instead recognizes it for what it is.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Later theorists have suggested additional responses, like using irony to take life less seriously or remaining ignorant of the responsible conflict.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some absurdists argue that whether and how one responds is insignificant.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This is based on the idea that if nothing really matters, then the human response toward this fact does not matter either.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The term "absurdism" is most closely associated with the philosophy of Albert Camus.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] However, important precursors and discussions of the absurd are also found in the works of Søren Kierkegaard.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Absurdism is intimately related to various other concepts and theories.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Its basic outlook is inspired by existentialist philosophy.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] However, existentialism includes additional theoretical commitments and often takes a more optimistic attitude toward the possibility of finding or creating meaning in one's life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Absurdism and nihilism share the belief that life is meaningless, but absurdists do not treat this as an isolated fact and are instead interested in the conflict between the human desire for meaning and the world's lack thereof.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Being confronted with this conflict may trigger an existential crisis, in which unpleasant experiences like anxiety or depression may push the affected to find a response for dealing with the conflict.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Recognizing the absence of objective meaning, however, does not preclude the conscious thinker from finding subjective meaning.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Absurdism is the philosophical thesis that life, or the world in general, is absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] There is wide agreement that the term "absurd" implies a lack of meaning or purpose, but there is also significant dispute concerning its exact definition and various versions have been suggested.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The choice of one's definition has important implications for whether the thesis of absurdism is correct and for the arguments cited for and against it: it may be true on one definition and false on another.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In a general sense, the absurd is that which lacks a sense, often because it involves some form of contradiction.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The absurd is paradoxical in the sense that it cannot be grasped by reason.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] But in the context of absurdism, the term is usually used in a more specific sense.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] According to most definitions, it involves a conflict, discrepancy, or collision between two things.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Opinions differ on what these two things are.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] For example, it is traditionally identified as the confrontation of rational man with an irrational world or as the attempt to grasp something based on reasons even though it is beyond the limits of rationality.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Similar definitions see the discrepancy between intention and outcome, between aspiration and reality, or between subjective assessment and objective worth as the source of absurdity.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Other definitions locate both conflicting sides within man: the ability to apprehend the arbitrariness of final ends and the inability to let go of commitments to them.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In regard to the conflict, absurdism differs from nihilism since it is not just the thesis that nothing matters.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Instead, it includes the component that things seem to matter to us nonetheless and that this impression cannot be shaken off.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This difference is expressed in the relational aspect of the absurd in that it constitutes a conflict between two sides.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Various components of the absurd have been suggested and different researchers often focus their definition and inquiry on one of these components.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some accounts emphasize the practical components concerned with the individual seeking meaning while others stress the theoretical components about being unable to know the world or to rationally grasp it.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] A different disagreement concerns whether the conflict exists only internal to the individual or is between the individual's expectations and the external world.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some theorists also include the metacognitive component that the absurd entails that the individual is aware of this conflict.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] An important aspect of absurdism is that the absurd is not limited to particular situations but encompasses life as a whole.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] There is a general agreement that people are often confronted with absurd situations in everyday life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] They often arise when there is a serious mismatch between one's intentions and reality.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] For example, a person struggling to break down a heavy front door is absurd if the house they are trying to break into lacks a back wall and could easily be entered on this route.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] But the philosophical thesis of absurdism is much more wide-reaching since it is not restricted to individual situations, persons, or phases in life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Instead, it asserts that life, or the world as a whole, is absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The claim that the absurd has such a global extension is controversial, in contrast to the weaker claim that some situations are absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The perspective of absurdism usually comes into view when the agent takes a step back from their individual everyday engagements with the world to assess their importance from a bigger context.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Such an assessment can result in the insight that the day-to-day engagements matter a lot to us despite the fact that they lack real meaning when evaluated from a wider perspective.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This assessment reveals the conflict between the significance seen from the internal perspective and the arbitrariness revealed through the external perspective.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The absurd becomes a problem since there is a strong desire for meaning and purpose even though they seem to be absent.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this sense, the conflict responsible for the absurd often either constitutes or is accompanied by an existential crisis.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] An important component of the absurd on the practical level concerns the seriousness people bring toward life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This seriousness is reflected in many different attitudes and areas, for example, concerning fame, pleasure, justice, knowledge, or survival, both in regard to ourselves as well as in regard to others.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] But there seems to be a discrepancy between how seriously we take our lives and the lives of others on the one hand, and how arbitrary they and the world at large seem to be on the other hand.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This can be understood in terms of importance and caring: it is absurd that people continue to care about these matters even though they seem to lack importance on an objective level.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The collision between these two sides can be defined as the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This is perhaps best exemplified when the agent is seriously engaged in choosing between arbitrary options, none of which truly matters.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] But usually, a distinction between absurdism and nihilism is made since absurdism involves the additional component that there is a conflict between man's desire for meaning and the absence of meaning.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] On a more theoretical view, absurdism is the belief that the world is, at its core, indifferent and impenetrable toward human attempts to uncover its deeper reason or that it cannot be known.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] According to this theoretical component, it involves the epistemological problem of the human limitations of knowing the world.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This includes the thesis that the world is in critical ways ungraspable to humans, both in relation to what to believe and how to act.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This is reflected in the chaos and irrationality of the universe, which acts according to its own laws in a manner indifferent to human concerns and aspirations.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It is closely related to the idea that the world remains silent when we ask why things are the way they are.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This silence arises from the impression that, on the most fundamental level, all things exist without a reason: they are simply there.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] An important aspect of these limitations to knowing the world is that they are essential to human cognition, i.e. they are not due to following false principles or accidental weaknesses but are inherent in the human cognitive faculties themselves.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some theorists also link this problem to the circularity of human reason, which is very skilled at producing chains of justification linking one thing to another while trying and failing to do the same for the chain of justification as a whole when taking a reflective step backward.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This implies that human reason is not just too limited to grasp life as a whole, but that, if one seriously tried to do so anyway, its ungrounded circularity might collapse and lead to madness.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] An important disagreement within the academic literature about the nature of absurdism and the absurd focuses specifically on whether the components responsible for the conflict are internal or external.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] According to the traditional position, the absurd has both internal and external components: it is due to the discrepancy between man's internal desire to lead a meaningful life and the external meaninglessness of the world.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this view, humans have, among their desires, some transcendent aspirations that seek a higher form of meaning in life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The distinction is important since, on the latter view, the absurd is built into human nature and would prevail no matter what the world was like.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] So, it is not just that absurdism is true in the actual world.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Instead, any possible world, even one that was designed by a divine god and guided by them according to their higher purpose, would still be equally absurd to man.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this sense, absurdity is the product of the power of our consciousness to take a step back from whatever it is considering and reflect on the reason of its object.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] When this process is applied to the world as a whole, including God, it is bound to fail its search for a reason or an explanation, no matter what the world is like.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this sense, absurdity arises from the conflict between features of ourselves: "our capacity to recognize the arbitrariness of our ultimate concerns and our simultaneous incapacity to relinquish our commitment to them".
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This view has the side effect that the absurd depends on the fact that the affected person recognizes it.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] For example, people who fail to apprehend the arbitrariness or the conflict would not be affected.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] According to some researchers, a central aspect of the absurd is that the agent is aware of the existence of the corresponding conflict.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This means that the person is conscious both of the seriousness they invest and of how it seems misplaced in an arbitrary world.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It also implies that other entities that lack this form of consciousness, like non-organic matter or lower life forms, are not absurd and are not faced with this particular problem.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some theorists also emphasize that the conflict remains despite the individual's awareness of it, i.e. that the individual continues to care about their everyday concerns despite their impression that, on the large scale, these concerns are meaningless.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Defenders of the metacognitive component have argued that it manages to explain why absurdity is primarily ascribed to human aspirations but not to lower animals: because they lack this metacognitive awareness.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] However, other researchers reject the metacognitive requirement based on the fact that it would severely limit the scope of the absurd to only those possibly few individuals who clearly recognize the contradiction while sparing the rest.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Thus, opponents have argued that not recognizing the conflict is just as absurd as consciously living through it.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Various popular arguments are often cited in favor of absurdism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some focus on the future by pointing out that nothing we do today will matter in a million years.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] A similar line of argument points to the fact that our lives are insignificant because of how small they are in relation to the universe as a whole, both concerning their spatial and their temporal dimensions.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The thesis of absurdism is also sometimes based on the problem of death, i.e. that there is no final end for us to pursue since we are all going to die.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this sense, death is said to destroy all our hard-earned achievements like career, wealth, or knowledge.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This argument is mitigated to some extent by the fact that we may have positive or negative effects on the lives of other people as well.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] But this does not fully solve the issue since the same problem, i.e. the lack of an ultimate end, applies to their lives as well.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Thomas Nagel has objected to these lines of argument based on the claim that they are circular: they assume rather than establish that life is absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] For example, the claim that our actions today will not matter in a million years does not directly imply that they do not matter today.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] And similarly, the fact that a process does not reach a meaningful ultimate goal does not entail that the process as a whole is worthless since some parts of the process may contain their justification without depending on a justification external to them.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Another argument proceeds indirectly by pointing out how various great thinkers have obvious irrational elements in their systems of thought.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] These purported mistakes of reason are then taken as signs of absurdism that were meant to hide or avoid it.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] From this perspective, the tendency to posit the existence of a benevolent God may be seen as a form of defense mechanism or wishful thinking to avoid an unsettling and inconvenient truth.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This is closely related to the idea that humans have an inborn desire for meaning and purpose, which is dwarfed by a meaningless and indifferent universe.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] A similar problematic step is taken by John Locke, who accepts the existence of a God beyond sensory experience, despite his strict empiricism, which demands that all knowledge be based on sensory experience.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Other theorists argue in favor of absurdism based on the claim that meaning is relational.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this sense, for something to be meaningful, it has to stand in relation to something else that is meaningful.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] For example, a word is meaningful because of its relation to a language or someone's life could be meaningful because this person dedicates their efforts to a higher meaningful project, like serving God or fighting poverty.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] An important consequence of this characterization of meaning is that it threatens to lead to an infinite regress: at each step, something is meaningful because something else is meaningful, which in its turn has meaning only because it is related to yet another meaningful thing, and so on.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This infinite chain and the corresponding absurdity could be avoided if some things had intrinsic or ultimate meaning, i.e. if their meaning did not depend on the meaning of something else.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] For example, if things on the large scale, like God or fighting poverty, had meaning, then our everyday engagements could be meaningful by standing in the right relation to them.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] However, if these wider contexts themselves lack meaning then they are unable to act as sources of meaning for other things.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This would lead to the absurd when understood as the conflict between the impression that our everyday engagements are meaningful even though they lack meaning because they do not stand in a relation to something else that is meaningful.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Another argument for absurdism is based on the attempt of assessing standards of what matters and why it matters.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It has been argued that the only way to answer such a question is in reference to these standards themselves.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This means that, in the end, it depends only on us, that "what seems to us important or serious or valuable would not seem so if we were differently constituted".
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The circularity and groundlessness of these standards themselves are then used to argue for absurdism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The most common criticism of absurdism is to argue that life in fact has meaning.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Supernaturalist arguments to this effect are based on the claim that God exists and acts as the source of meaning.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Naturalist arguments, on the other hand, contend that various sources of meaning can be found in the natural world without recourse to a supernatural realm.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some of them hold that meaning is subjective.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] On this view, whether a given thing is meaningful varies from person to person based on their subjective attitude toward this thing.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Others find meaning in external values, for example, in morality, knowledge, or beauty.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] All these different positions have in common that they affirm the existence of meaning, in contrast to absurdism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Another criticism of absurdism focuses on its negative attitude toward moral values.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In the absurdist literature, the moral dimension is sometimes outright denied, for example, by holding that value judgments are to be discarded or that the rejection of God implies the rejection of moral values.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] On this view, absurdism brings with it a highly controversial form of moral nihilism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This means that there is a lack, not just of a higher purpose in life, but also of moral values.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] These two sides can be linked by the idea that without a higher purpose, nothing is worth pursuing that could give one's life meaning.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This worthlessness seems to apply to morally relevant actions equally as to other issues.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this sense, "[b]elief in the meaning of life always implies a scale of values" while "[b]elief in the absurd ... teaches the contrary".
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Various objections to such a position have been presented, for example, that it violates common sense or that it leads to numerous radical consequences, like that no one is ever guilty of any blameworthy behavior or that there are no ethical rules.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] But this negative attitude toward moral values is not always consistently maintained by absurdists and some of the suggested responses on how to deal with the absurd seem to explicitly defend the existence of moral values.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Due to this ambiguity, other critics of absurdism have objected to it based on its inconsistency.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The moral values defended by absurdists often overlap with the ethical outlook of existentialism and include traits like sincerity, authenticity, and courage as virtues.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this sense, absurdists often argue that it matters how the agent faces the absurdity of their situation and that the response should exemplify these virtues.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This aspect is particularly prominent in the idea that the agent should rebel against the absurd and live their life authentically as a form of passionate revolt.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some see the latter position as inconsistent with the idea that there is no meaning in life: if nothing matters then it should also not matter how we respond to this fact.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Defenders of absurdism have tried to resist this line of argument by contending that, in contrast to other responses, it remains true to the basic insight of absurdism and the "logic of the absurd" by acknowledging the existence of the absurd instead of denying it.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] But this defense is not always accepted.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] One of its shortcomings seems to be that it commits the is-ought fallacy: absurdism presents itself as a descriptive claim about the existence and nature of the absurd but then goes on to posit various normative claims.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Another defense of absurdism consists in weakening the claims about how one should respond to the absurd and which virtues such a response should exemplify.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] On this view, absurdism may be understood as a form of self-help that merely provides prudential advice.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Such prudential advice may be helpful to certain people without pretending to have the status of universally valid moral values or categorical normative judgments.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] So the value of the prudential advice may merely be relative to the interests of some people but not valuable in a more general sense.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This way, absurdists have tried to resolve the apparent inconsistency in their position.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] According to absurdism, life in general is absurd: the absurd is not just limited to a few specific cases.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Nonetheless, some cases are more paradigmatic examples than others.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] *The Myth of Sisyphus* is often treated as a key example of the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In it, Zeus punishes King Sisyphus by compelling him to roll a massive boulder up a hill.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Whenever the boulder reaches the top, it rolls down again, thereby forcing Sisyphus to repeat the same task all over again throughout eternity.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This story may be seen as an absurdist parable for the hopelessness and futility of human life in general: just like Sisyphus, humans in general are condemned to toil day in and day out in the attempt to fulfill pointless tasks, which will be replaced by new pointless tasks once they are completed.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It has been argued that a central aspect of Sisyphus' situation is not just the futility of his labor but also his awareness of the futility.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Another example of the absurdist aspect of the human condition is given in Franz Kafka's *The Trial*.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In it, the protagonist Josef K. is arrested and prosecuted by an inaccessible authority even though he is convinced that he has done nothing wrong.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Throughout the story, he desperately tries to discover what crimes he is accused of and how to defend himself.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] But in the end, he lets go of his futile attempts and submits to his execution without ever finding out what he was accused of.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The absurd nature of the world is exemplified by the mysterious and impenetrable functioning of the judicial system, which seems indifferent to Josef K. and resists all of his attempts of making sense of it.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Philosophers of absurdism often complain that the topic of the absurd does not receive the attention of professional philosophers it merits, especially when compared to other perennial philosophical areas of inquiry.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It has been argued, for example, that this can be seen in the tendency of various philosophers throughout the ages to include the epistemically dubitable existence of God in their philosophical systems as a source of ultimate explanation of the mysteries of existence.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In that regard, this tendency may be seen as a form of defense mechanism or wishful thinking constituting a side-effect of the unacknowledged and ignored importance of the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] While some discussions of absurdism happen explicitly in the philosophical literature, it is often presented in a less explicit manner in the form of novels or plays.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] These presentations usually happen by telling stories that exemplify some of the key aspects of absurdism even though they may not explicitly discuss the topic.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It has been argued that acknowledging the existence of the absurd has important consequences for epistemology, especially in relation to philosophy but also when applied more widely to other fields.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The reason for this is that acknowledging the absurd includes becoming aware of human cognitive limitations and may lead to a form of epistemic humbleness.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The impression that life is absurd may in some cases have serious psychological consequences like triggering an existential crisis.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this regard, an awareness both of absurdism itself and the possible responses to it can be central to avoiding or resolving such consequences.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Most researchers argue that the basic conflict posed by the absurd cannot be truly resolved.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This means that any attempt to do so is bound to fail even though their protagonists may not be aware of their failure.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] On this view, there are still several possible responses, some better than others, but none able to solve the fundamental conflict.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Traditional absurdism, as exemplified by Albert Camus, holds that there are three possible responses to absurdism: suicide, religious belief, or revolting against the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Later researchers have suggested more ways of responding to absurdism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] A very blunt and simple response, though quite radical, is to commit suicide.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] According to Camus, for example, the problem of suicide is the only "really serious philosophical problem".
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It consists in seeking an answer to the question "Should I kill myself?".
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This response is motivated by the insight that, no matter how hard the agent tries, they may never reach their goal of leading a meaningful life, which can then justify the rejection of continuing to live at all.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Most researchers acknowledge that this is one form of response to the absurd but reject it due to its radical and irreversible nature and argue instead for a different approach.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] One such alternative response to the apparent absurdity of life is to assume that there is some higher ultimate purpose in which the individual may participate, like service to society, progress of history, or God's glory.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] While the individual may only play a small part in the realization of this overarching purpose, it may still act as a source of meaning.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This way, the individual may find meaning and thereby escape the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] One serious issue with this approach is that the problem of absurdity applies to this alleged higher purpose as well.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] So just like the aims of a single individual life can be put into doubt, this applies equally to a larger purpose shared by many.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] And if this purpose is itself absurd, it fails to act as a source of meaning for the individual participating in it.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Camus identifies this response as a form of suicide as well, pertaining not to the physical but to the philosophical level.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It is a philosophical suicide in the sense that the individual just assumes that the chosen higher purpose is meaningful and thereby fails to reflect on its absurdity.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Traditional absurdists usually reject both physical and philosophical suicide as the recommended response to the absurd, usually with the argument that both these responses constitute some form of escape that fails to face the absurd for what it is.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Despite the gravity and inevitability of the absurd, they recommend that we should face it directly, i.e. not escape from it by retreating into the illusion of false hope or by ending one's life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In this sense, accepting the reality of the absurd means rejecting any hopes for a happy afterlife free of those contradictions.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Instead, the individual should acknowledge the absurd and engage in a rebellion against it.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Such a revolt usually exemplifies certain virtues closely related to existentialism, like the affirmation of one's freedom in the face of adversity as well as accepting responsibility and defining one's own essence.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] An important aspect of this lifestyle is that life is lived passionately and intensely by inviting and seeking new experiences.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Such a lifestyle might be exemplified by an actor, a conqueror, or a seduction artist who is constantly on the lookout for new roles, conquests, or attractive people despite their awareness of the absurdity of these enterprises.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Another aspect lies in creativity, i.e. that the agent sees themselves as and acts as the creator of their own works and paths in life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This constitutes a form of rebellion in the sense that the agent remains aware of the absurdity of the world and their part in it but keeps on opposing it instead of resigning and admitting defeat.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] But this response does not solve the problem of the absurd at its core: even a life dedicated to the rebellion against the absurd is itself still absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Defenders of the rebellious response to absurdism have pointed out that, despite its possible shortcomings, it has one important advantage over many of its alternatives: it manages to accept the absurd for what it is without denying it by rejecting that it exists or by stopping one's own existence.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Some even hold that it is the only philosophically coherent response to the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] While these three responses are the most prominent ones in the traditional absurdist literature, various other responses have also been suggested.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Instead of rebellion, for example, absurdism may also lead to a form of irony.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This irony is not sufficient to escape the absurdity of life altogether, but it may mitigate it to some extent by distancing oneself to some degree from the seriousness of life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] According to Thomas Nagel, there may be, at least theoretically, two responses to actually resolving the problem of the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This is based on the idea that the absurd arises from the consciousness of a conflict between two aspects of human life: that humans care about various things and that the world seems arbitrary and does not merit this concern.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The absurd would not arise if either of the conflicting elements would cease to exist, i.e. if the individual would stop caring about things, as some Eastern religions seem to suggest, or if one could find something that possesses a non-arbitrary meaning that merits the concern.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] For theorists who give importance to the consciousness of this conflict for the absurd, a further option presents itself: to remain ignorant of it to the extent that this is possible.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Other theorists hold that a proper response to the absurd may neither be possible nor necessary, that it just remains one of the basic aspects of life no matter how it is confronted.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This lack of response may be justified through the thesis of absurdism itself: if nothing really matters on the grand scale, then this applies equally to human responses toward this fact.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] From this perspective, the passionate rebellion against an apparently trivial or unimportant state of affairs seems less like a heroic quest and more like a fool's errand.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Jeffrey Gordon has objected to this criticism based on the claim that there is a difference between absurdity and lack of importance.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] So even if life as a whole is absurd, some facts about life may still be more important than others and the fact that life as a whole is absurd would be a good candidate for the more important facts.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Certain precursors to absurdism are found in Ecclesiastes, a book of the Bible, and in the works of William Shakespeare.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Absurdism has its origins in the work of the 19th-century Danish philosopher Søren Kierkegaard, who chose to confront the crisis that humans face with the Absurd by developing his own existentialist philosophy.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Absurdism as a belief system was born of the European existentialist movement that ensued, specifically when Camus rejected certain aspects of that philosophical line of thought and published his essay *The Myth of Sisyphus*.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The aftermath of World War II provided the social environment that stimulated absurdist views and allowed for their popular development, especially in the devastated country of France.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Foucault viewed Shakespearean theater as a precursor of absurdism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] An idea very close to the concept of the absurd is due to Immanuel Kant, who distinguishes between phenomena and noumena.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This distinction refers to the gap between how things appear to us and what they are like in themselves.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] For example, according to Kant, space and times are dimensions belonging to the realm of phenomena since this is how sensory impressions are organized by the mind, but may not be found on the level of noumena.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The concept of the absurd corresponds to the thesis that there is such a gap and human limitations may limit the mind from ever truly grasping reality, i.e. that reality in this sense remains absurd to the mind.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] A century before Camus, the 19th-century Danish philosopher Søren Kierkegaard wrote extensively about the absurdity of the world.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] — Kierkegaard, *Concluding Unscientific Postscript*, 1846, Hong 1992, p.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] How can this absurdity be held or believed?
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Kierkegaard provides an example in *Fear and Trembling* (1843), which was published under the pseudonym *Johannes de Silentio*.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In the story of Abraham in the Book of Genesis, Abraham is told by God to kill his son Isaac.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Just as Abraham is about to kill Isaac, an angel stops Abraham from doing so.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Kierkegaard believes that through virtue of the absurd, Abraham, defying all reason and ethical duties ("you cannot act"), got back his son and reaffirmed his faith ("where I have to act").
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Another instance of absurdist themes in Kierkegaard's work appears in *The Sickness Unto Death*, which Kierkegaard signed with pseudonym *Anti-Climacus*.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Exploring the forms of despair, Kierkegaard examines the type of despair known as defiance.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] According to Kierkegaard in his autobiography *The Point of View of My Work as an Author*, most of his pseudonymous writings are not necessarily reflective of his own opinions.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Nevertheless, his work anticipated many absurdist themes and provided its theoretical background.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The philosophy of Albert Camus, or more precisely the "camusian absurd" (French : *l'absurde camusien*), refers with absurdism to the work and philosophical thought of the French writer Albert Camus.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This philosophy is influenced by the author's political, libertarian, social and ecological ideas; and is inspired by previous philosophical trends, such as Greek philosophy, nihilism, the Nietzschean thought or existentialism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It revolves around three major cycles: "the absurd (*l'absurde*)", "the revolt (*la révolte*)" and "love (*l'amour*)".
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Each cycle is linked to a Greek myth (Sisyphus, Prometheus, Nemesis) and explores specific themes and objects; the common thread remaining the solitude and despair of the human, constantly driven by the tireless search for the meaning of the world and of life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] — Albert Camus at Stockholm in 1957, quoted by Roger Quilliot in *Essais*, II, p.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The cycle of the absurd, or *negation*, primarily addresses suicide and the human condition.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] It is expressed through four of Camus's works: the novel *The Stranger* and the essay *The Myth of Sisyphus* (1942), then the plays *Caligula* and *The Misunderstanding* (1944).
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] By refusing the refuge of belief, Human becomes aware that his existence revolves around repetitive and meaningless acts.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The certainty of death only reinforces, according to the writer, the feeling of uselessness of all existence.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The absurd is therefore the feeling that man feels when confronted with the absence of meaning in the face of the Universe, the painful realization of his separation from the world.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The question then arises of the legitimacy of suicide.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The cycle of revolt, called *the positive*, is a direct response to the absurd and is also expressed by four of his works: the novel *The Plague* (1947), the plays *The State of Siege* (1948) and *The Just Assassins* (1949), then the essay *The Rebel* (1951).
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Depriving ourselves of eternal life frees us from the constraints imposed by an improbable future; Man gains freedom of action, lucidity and dignity.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The philosophy of Camus therefore has as its finitude a singular humanism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Advancing a message of lucidity, resilience and emancipation in the face of the absurdity of life, it encourages people to create their own meanings through personal choices and commitments, and to embrace their freedom to the fullest.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Because he affirms that, even in the absurd, there is room for passion and rebellion; and although the Universe may be indifferent to our search for meaning, this search is *in itself* meaningful.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In *The Myth of Sisyphus*, despite his absurd destiny, Sisyphus finds a form of liberation in his incessant work: "one must imagine Sisyphus happy".
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] With the cycle of love and the "midday thought" (French: *la pensée de midi*), the philosophy of the absurd is completed by a principle of measurement and pleasure, close to Epicureanism.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Though the notion of the 'absurd' pervades all Albert Camus's writing, *The Myth of Sisyphus* is his chief work on the subject.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In it, Camus considers absurdity as a confrontation, an opposition, a conflict or a "divorce" between two ideals.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Specifically, he defines the human condition as absurd, as the confrontation between man's desire for significance, meaning and clarity on the one hand—and the silent, cold universe on the other.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] He continues that there are specific human experiences evoking notions of absurdity.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Such a realization or encounter with the absurd leaves the individual with a choice: suicide, a leap of faith, or recognition.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] He concludes that recognition is the only defensible option.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] For Camus, suicide is a "confession" that life is not worth living; it is a choice that implicitly declares that life is "too much." Suicide offers the most basic "way out" of absurdity: the immediate termination of the self and its place in the universe.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The absurd encounter can also arouse a "leap of faith," a term derived from one of Kierkegaard's early pseudonyms, *Johannes de Silentio* (although the term was not used by Kierkegaard himself), where one believes that there is more than the rational life (aesthetic or ethical).
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] To take a "leap of faith," one must act with the "virtue of the absurd" (as *Johannes de Silentio* put it), where a suspension of the ethical may need to exist.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] This faith has no expectations, but is a flexible power initiated by a recognition of the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Camus states that because the leap of faith escapes rationality and defers to abstraction over personal experience, the leap of faith is not absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Camus considers the leap of faith as "philosophical suicide," rejecting both this and physical suicide.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Lastly, a person can choose to embrace the absurd condition.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] According to Camus, one's freedom—and the opportunity to give life meaning—lies in the recognition of absurdity.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] If the absurd experience is truly the realization that the universe is fundamentally devoid of absolutes, then we as individuals are truly free.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] "To live without appeal," as he puts it, is a philosophical move to define absolutes and universals subjectively, rather than objectively.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The freedom of man is thus established in one's natural ability and opportunity to create their own meaning and purpose; to decide (or think) for oneself.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] The individual becomes the most precious unit of existence, representing a set of unique ideals that can be characterized as an entire universe in its own right.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] In acknowledging the absurdity of seeking any inherent meaning, but continuing this search regardless, one can be happy, gradually developing meaning from the search alone.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] *"Happiness and the absurd are two sons of the same earth.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p01] Camus states in *The Myth of Sisyphus*: "Thus I draw from the absurd three consequences, which are my revolt, my freedom, and my passion.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] Absurdism originated from (as well as alongside) the 20th-century strains of existentialism and nihilism; it shares some prominent starting points with both, though also entails conclusions that are uniquely distinct from these other schools of thought.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] All three arose from the human experience of anguish and confusion stemming from existence: the apparent meaninglessness of a world in which humans, nevertheless, are compelled to find or create meaning.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] The three schools of thought diverge from there.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] Existentialists have generally advocated the individual's construction of their own meaning in life as well as the free will of the individual.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] Absurdists following Camus also devalue or outright reject free will, encouraging merely that the individual live defiantly and authentically *in spite of* the psychological tension of the Absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] Both existentialism and absurdism entail consideration of the practical applications of becoming conscious of the truth of existential nihilism: i.e., how a driven seeker of meaning should act when suddenly confronted with the seeming concealment, or downright absence, of meaning in the universe.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] While absurdism can be seen as a kind of response to existentialism, it can be debated exactly how substantively the two positions differ from each other.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] The existentialist, after all, does not deny the reality of death.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] But the absurdist seems to reaffirm the way in which death ultimately nullifies our meaning-making activities, a conclusion the existentialists seem to resist through various notions of posterity or, in Sartre's case, participation in a grand humanist project.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] The basic problem of absurdism is usually not encountered through a dispassionate philosophical inquiry but as the manifestation of an existential crisis.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] Existential crises are inner conflicts in which the individual wrestles with the impression that life lacks meaning.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] They are accompanied by various negative experiences, such as stress, anxiety, despair, and depression, which can disturb the individual's normal functioning in everyday life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] In this sense, the conflict underlying the absurdist perspective poses a psychological challenge to the affected.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] This challenge is due to the impression that the agent's vigorous daily engagement stands in incongruity with its apparent insignificance encountered through philosophical reflection.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] Realizing this incongruity is usually not a pleasant occurrence and may lead to estrangement, alienation, and hopelessness.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] The intimate relation to psychological crises is also manifested in the problem of finding the right response to this unwelcome conflict, for example, by denying it, by taking life less seriously, or by revolting against the absurd.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] But accepting the position of absurdism may also have certain positive psychological effects.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] In this sense, it can help the individual achieve a certain psychological distance from unexamined dogmas and thus help them evaluate their situation from a more encompassing and objective perspective.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] However, it brings with it the danger of leveling all significant differences and thereby making it difficult for the individual to decide what to do or how to live their life.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] It has been argued that absurdism in the practical domain resembles epistemological skepticism in the theoretical domain.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] In the case of epistemology, we usually take for granted our knowledge of the world around us even though, when methodological doubt is applied, it turns out that this knowledge is not as unshakable as initially assumed.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] For example, the agent may decide to trust their perception that the sun is shining but its reliability depends on the assumption that the agent is not dreaming, which they would not know even if they were dreaming.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] In a similar sense in the practical domain, the agent may decide to take aspirin in order to avoid a headache even though they may be unable to give a reason for why they should be concerned with their own wellbeing at all.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] In both cases, the agent goes ahead with a form of unsupported natural confidence and takes life largely for granted despite the fact that their power to justify is only limited to a rather small range and fails when applied to the larger context, on which the small range depends.
[src:antinatalism/absurdism-p02] It has been argued that absurdism is opposed to various fundamental principles and assumptions guiding education, like the importance of truth and of fostering rationality in the students.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Unlike guardianship or other systems designed for the care of the young, adoption is intended to effect a permanent change in status and as such requires societal recognition, either through legal or religious sanction.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Historically, some societies have enacted specific laws governing adoption, while others used less formal means (notably contracts that specified inheritance rights and parental responsibilities without an accompanying transfer of filiation).
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Modern systems of adoption, arising in the 20th century, tend to be governed by comprehensive statutes and regulations.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] While the modern form of adoption emerged in the United States, forms of the practice appeared throughout history.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The Code of Hammurabi, for example, details the rights of adopters and the responsibilities of adopted individuals at length.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The practice of adoption in ancient Rome is well-documented in the Codex Justinianus.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Markedly different from the modern period, ancient adoption practices put emphasis on the political and economic interests of the adopter, providing a legal tool that strengthened political ties between wealthy families and created male heirs to manage estates.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The use of adoption by the aristocracy is well-documented: many of Rome's emperors were adopted sons.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Adrogation was a kind of Roman adoption in which the person adopted consented to be adopted by another.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Infant adoption during Antiquity appears rare.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Abandoned children were often picked up for slavery and composed a significant percentage of the Empire's slave supply.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Roman legal records indicate that foundlings were occasionally taken in by families and raised as a son or daughter.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Although not normally adopted under Roman Law, the children, called *alumni*, were reared in an arrangement similar to guardianship, being considered the property of the father who abandoned them.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Other ancient civilizations, notably India and China, used some form of adoption as well.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Evidence suggests the goal of this practice was to ensure the continuity of cultural and religious practices; in contrast to the Western idea of extending family lines.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In ancient India, adoption was conducted in a limited and highly ritualistic form, so that an adopter might have the necessary funerary rites performed by a son.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] China had a similar idea of adoption with males adopted solely to perform the duties of ancestor worship.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The practice of adopting the children of family members and close friends was common among the cultures of Polynesia including Hawaii where the custom was referred to as *hānai*.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The nobility of the Germanic, Celtic, and Slavic cultures that dominated Europe after the decline of the Roman Empire denounced the practice of adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In medieval society, bloodlines were paramount; a ruling dynasty lacking a "natural-born" heir apparent was replaced, a stark contrast to Roman traditions.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The evolution of European law reflects this aversion to adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] English common law, for instance, did not permit adoption since it contradicted the customary rules of inheritance.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In the same vein, France's Napoleonic Code made adoption difficult, requiring adopters to be over the age of 50, sterile, older than the adopted person by at least 15 years, and to have fostered the adoptee for at least six years.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Some adoptions continued to occur, however, but became informal, based on ad hoc contracts.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] For example, in the year 737, in a charter from the town of Lucca, three adoptees were made heirs to an estate.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Like other contemporary arrangements, the agreement stressed the responsibility of the adopted rather than adopter, focusing on the fact that, under the contract, the adoptive father was meant to be cared for in his old age; an idea that is similar to the conceptions of adoption under Roman law.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Europe's cultural makeover marked a period of significant innovation for adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Without support from the nobility, the practice gradually shifted toward abandoned children.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Abandonment levels rose with the fall of the empire and many of the foundlings were left on the doorstep of the Church.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Initially, the clergy reacted by drafting rules to govern the exposing, selling, and rearing of abandoned children.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The Church's innovation, however, was the practice of oblation, whereby children were dedicated to lay life within monastic institutions and reared within a monastery.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] This created the first system in European history in which abandoned children did not have legal, social, or moral disadvantages.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] As a result, many of Europe's abandoned and orphaned children became alumni of the Church, which in turn took the role of adopter.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Oblation marks the beginning of a shift toward institutionalization, eventually bringing about the establishment of the foundling hospital and orphanage.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] As the idea of institutional care gained acceptance, formal rules appeared about how to place children into families: boys could become apprenticed to an artisan and girls might be married off under the institution's authority.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Institutions informally adopted out children as well, a mechanism treated as a way to obtain cheap labor, demonstrated by the fact that when the adopted died their bodies were returned by the family to the institution for burial.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] This system of apprenticeship and informal adoption extended into the 19th century, today seen as a transitional phase for adoption history.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Under the direction of social welfare activists, orphan asylums began to promote adoptions based on sentiment rather than work; children were placed out under agreements to provide care for them as family members instead of under contracts for apprenticeship.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The growth of this model is believed to have contributed to the enactment of the first modern adoption law in 1851 by the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, unique in that it codified the ideal of the "best interests of the child".
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Despite its intent, though, in practice, the system operated much the same as earlier incarnations.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The experience of the Boston Female Asylum (BFA) is a good example, which had up to 30% of its charges adopted out by 1888.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The next stage of adoption's evolution fell to the emerging nation of the United States.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Rapid immigration and the American Civil War resulted in unprecedented overcrowding of orphanages and foundling homes in the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Charles Loring Brace, a Protestant minister, became appalled by the legions of homeless waifs roaming the streets of New York City.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Brace considered the abandoned youth, particularly Catholics, to be the most dangerous element challenging the city's order.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] His solution was outlined in *The Best Method of Disposing of Our Pauper and Vagrant Children* (1859), which started the Orphan Train movement.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The orphan trains eventually shipped an estimated 200,000 children from the urban centers of the East to the nation's rural regions.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The children were generally indentured, rather than adopted, to families who took them in.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] As in times past, some children were raised as members of the family while others were used as farm laborers and household servants.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The sheer size of the displacement—one of the largest migrations of children in history—and the degree of exploitation that occurred, gave rise to new agencies and a series of laws that promoted adoption arrangements rather than indenture.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The hallmark of the period is Minnesota's adoption law of 1917, which mandated investigation of all placements and limited record access to those involved in the adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] During the same period, the Progressive movement swept the United States with a critical goal of ending the prevailing orphanage system.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] As late as 1923, only two percent of children without parental care were in adoptive homes, with the balance in foster arrangements and orphanages.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Less than forty years later, nearly one-third were in adoptive homes.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Nevertheless, the popularity of eugenic ideas in America put up obstacles to the growth of adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] There were grave concerns about the genetic quality of illegitimate and indigent children, perhaps best exemplified by the influential writings of Henry H.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The period 1945 to 1974, the baby scoop era, saw rapid growth and acceptance of adoption as a means to build a family.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Illegitimate births rose three-fold after World War II, as sexual mores changed.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Simultaneously, the scientific community began to stress the dominance of nurture over genetics, chipping away at eugenic stigmas.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In this environment, adoption became the obvious solution for infertile couples.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Many of the mothers, however, were forced or coerced into relinquishing their children.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Taken together, these trends resulted in a new American model for adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Following its Roman predecessor, Americans severed the rights of the original parents while making adopters the new parents in the eyes of the law.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The origin of the move toward secrecy began with Charles Loring Brace, who introduced it to prevent children from the Orphan Trains from returning to or being reclaimed by their parents.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Brace feared the impact of the parents' poverty, in general, and Catholic religion, in particular, on the youth.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] This tradition of secrecy was carried on by the later Progressive reformers when drafting of American laws.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The number of adoptions in the United States peaked in 1970.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The years of the late 1960s and early 1970s saw a dramatic change in society's view of illegitimacy and in the legal rights of those born outside of wedlock.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In response, family preservation efforts grew so that few children born out of wedlock today are adopted.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Ironically, adoption is far more visible and discussed in society today, yet it is less common.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The American model of adoption eventually proliferated globally.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] England and Wales established their first formal adoption law in 1926.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Sweden made adoptees full members of the family in 1959.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] West Germany enacted its first laws in 1977.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Additionally, the Asian powers opened their orphanage systems to adoption, influenced as they were by Western ideas following colonial rule and military occupation.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In France, local public institutions accredit candidates for adoption, who can then contact orphanages abroad or ask for the support of NGOs.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The system does not involve fees, but gives considerable power to social workers whose decisions may restrict adoption to "standard" families (middle-age, medium to high income, heterosexual, Caucasian).
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The table below provides a snapshot of Western adoption rates.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Adoption in the United States still occurs at rates nearly three times those of its peers even though the number of children awaiting adoption has held steady in recent years, between 100,000 and 125,000 during the period 2009 to 2018.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Contemporary adoption practices can be open or closed.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Adoptions can occur between related or unrelated individuals.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Historically, most adoptions occurred within a family.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The most recent data from the U.S. indicates that about half of adoptions are currently between related individuals.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] A common example of this is a "step-parent adoption", where the new partner of a parent legally adopts a child from the parent's previous relationship.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Intra-family adoption can also occur through surrender, as a result of parental death, or when the child cannot otherwise be cared for and a family member agrees to take over.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Adoption is not always a voluntary process.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In some countries, for example in the U.K., one of the main origins of children being placed for adoption is that they have been removed from the birth home, often by a government body such as the local authority.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] There are a number of reasons why children are removed including abuse and neglect, which can have a lasting impact on the adoptee.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Social workers in many cases will be notified of a safeguarding concern in relation to a child and will make enquiries into the child's well-being.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Social workers will often seek means of keeping a child together with the birth family, for example, by providing additional support to the family before considering removal of a child.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] A court of law will often then make decisions regarding the child's future, for example, whether they can return to the birth family, enter into foster care or be adopted.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Infertility is the main reason parents seek to adopt children they are not related to.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] One study shows this accounted for 80% of unrelated infant adoptions and half of adoptions through foster care.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Estimates suggest that 11–24% of Americans who cannot conceive or carry to term attempt to build a family through adoption, and that the overall rate of never-married American women who adopt is about 1.4%.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Other reasons people adopt are numerous although not well documented.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Although there are a range of reasons, the most recent study of experiences of women who adopt suggests they are most likely to be 40–44 years of age, to be currently married, to have impaired fertility, and to be childless.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Although adoption is often described as forming a "forever" family, the relationship can be ended at any time.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The legal termination of an adoption is called disruption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In U.S. terminology, adoptions are *disrupted* if they are ended before being finalized, and they are *dissolved* if the relationship is ended afterwards.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] It may also be called a *failed adoption*.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] After legal finalization, the disruption process is usually initiated by adoptive parents via a court petition and is analogous to divorce proceedings.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] It is a legal avenue unique to adoptive parents as disruption/dissolution does not apply to biological kin, although biological family members are sometimes disowned or abandoned.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The wide range of values reflects the paucity of information on the subject and demographic factors such as age; it is known that teenagers are more prone to having their adoptions disrupted than young children.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Joint adoption by same-sex couples is legal in 34 countries as of March 2022, and additionally in various sub-national territories.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Adoption may also be in the form of stepchild adoption (6 additional countries), wherein one partner in a same-sex couple adopts the child of the other.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Most countries that have same-sex marriage allow joint adoption by those couples, the exceptions being Ecuador (no adoption by same-sex couples), Taiwan (stepchild adoption only) and Mexico (in one third of states with same-sex marriage).
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] A few countries with civil unions or lesser marriage rights nonetheless allow step- or joint adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey (ACS) enhanced its approach to measuring same-sex couple households, explicitly distinguishing between same-sex and opposite-sex spouses or partners.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Same-sex parents, according to the ACS in 2022, were predominantly female.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Notably, 26.8% of female same-sex couple households had children under 18, in contrast to 8.2% of male same-sex couple households.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In homes with children, female same-sex couples were almost 12% more likely to have biological children compared with male same-sex couples; however, male same-sex couples were 18.5% more likely to adopt and were less likely to have stepchildren.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] The biological relationship between a parent and child is important, and the separation of the two has led to concerns about adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] This theory is supported in another more qualitative study wherein adoptive relationships marked by sameness in likes, personality, and appearance, were associated with both adult adoptees and adoptive parents reporting being happier with the adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Other studies provide evidence that adoptive relationships can form along other lines.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Noting that adoptees seemed to be more likely to experience problems such as drug addiction, the study speculated that adoptive parents might invest more in adoptees not because they favor them, but because they are more likely than genetic children to need the help.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Psychologists' findings regarding the importance of early mother-infant bonding created some concern about whether parents who adopt older infants or toddlers after birth have missed some crucial period for the child's development.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Beyond the foundational issues, the unique questions posed for adoptive parents are varied.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] They include how to respond to stereotypes, answering questions about heritage, and how best to maintain connections with biological kin when in an open adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] One author suggests a common question adoptive parents have is: "Will we love the child even though he/she is not our biological child?" A specific concern for many parents is accommodating an adoptee in the classroom.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Familiar lessons like "draw your family tree" or "trace your eye color back through your parents and grandparents to see where your genes come from" could be hurtful to children who were adopted and do not know this biological information.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Numerous suggestions have been made to substitute new lessons, e.g., focusing on "family orchards".
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Adopting older children presents other parenting issues.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Some children from foster care have histories of maltreatment, such as physical and psychological neglect, physical abuse, and sexual abuse, and are at risk of developing psychiatric problems.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Such children are at risk of developing a disorganized attachment.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] (1990, 1995) found that 80% of abused and maltreated infants in their sample exhibited disorganized attachment styles.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Disorganized attachment is associated with a number of developmental problems, including dissociative symptoms, as well as depressive, anxious, and acting-out symptoms.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] "Attachment is an active process—it can be secure or insecure, maladaptive or productive." In the U.K., some adoptions fail because the adoptive parents do not get sufficient support to deal with difficult, traumatized children.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] This is a false economy as local authority care for these children is extremely expensive.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Similar mechanisms appear to be at work in the physical development of adoptees.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Danish and American researchers conducting studies on the genetic contribution to body mass index found correlations between an adoptee's weight class and his biological parents' BMI while finding no relationship with the adoptive family environment.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Moreover, about one-half of inter-individual differences were due to individual non-shared influences.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] These differences in development appear to play out in the way young adoptees deal with major life events.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In the case of parental divorce, adoptees have been found to respond differently from children who have not been adopted.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Recent research has shown that adoptive parenting may have impacts on adoptive children, it has been shown that warm adoptive parenting reduces internalizing and externalizing problems of the adoptive children over time.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Another study shows that warm adoptive parenting at 27 months predicted lower levels of child externalizing problems at ages 6 and 7.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Several factors affect the decision to release or raise the child.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] White adolescents tend to give up their babies to non-relatives, whereas black adolescents are more likely to receive support from their own community in raising the child and also in the form of informal adoption by relatives.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Studies by Leynes and by Festinger and Young, Berkman, and Rehr found that, for pregnant adolescents, the decision to release the child for adoption depended on the attitude toward adoption held by the adolescent's mother.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Another study found that pregnant adolescents whose mothers had a higher level of education were more likely to release their babies for adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Research suggests that women who choose to release their babies for adoption are more likely to be younger, enrolled in school, and have lived in a two-parent household at age 10, than those who kept and raised their babies.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] There is limited research on the consequences of adoption for the original parents, and the findings have been mixed.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] One study found that those who released their babies for adoption were less comfortable with their decision than those who kept their babies.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] However, levels of comfort over both groups were high, and those who released their child were similar to those who kept their child in ratings of life satisfaction, relationship satisfaction, and positive future outlook for schooling, employment, finances, and marriage.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Subsequent research found that adolescent mothers who chose to release their babies for adoption were more likely to experience feelings of sorrow and regret over their decision than those who kept their babies.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] However, these feelings decreased significantly from one year after birth to the end of the second year.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] More recent research found that in a sample of mothers who had released their children for adoption four to 12 years prior, every participant had frequent thoughts of their lost child.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] For most, thoughts were both negative and positive in that they produced both feelings of sadness and joy.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Those who experienced the greatest portion of positive thoughts were those who had open, rather than closed or time-limited mediated, adoptions.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] In another study that compared mothers who released their children to those who raised them, mothers who released their children were more likely to delay their next pregnancy, to delay marriage, and to complete job training.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] However, both groups reached lower levels of education than their peers who were never pregnant.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Another study found similar consequences for choosing to release a child for adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Adolescent mothers who released their children were more likely to reach a higher level of education and to be employed than those who kept their children.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] They also waited longer before having their next child.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Most of the research that exists on adoption effects on the birth parents was conducted with samples of adolescents, or with women who were adolescents when carrying their babies—little data exists for birth parents from other populations.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p01] Furthermore, there is a lack of longitudinal data that may elucidate long-term social and psychological consequences for birth parents who choose to place their children for adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Previous research on adoption has led to assumptions that indicate that there is a heightened risk in terms of psychological development and social relationships for adoptees.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Yet, such assumptions have been clarified as flawed due to methodological failures.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] But more recent studies have been supportive in indicating more accurate information and results about the similarities, differences and overall lifestyles of adoptees.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adoptees are four times more likely to attempt suicide than other people.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Evidence about the development of adoptees can be supported in newer studies.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] It can be said that adoptees, in some respect, tend to develop differently from the general population.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] This can be seen in many aspects of life, but usually can be found as a greater risk around the time of adolescence.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] For example, it has been found that many adoptees experience difficulty in establishing a sense of identity.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] There are many ways in which the concept of identity can be defined.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] It is true in all cases that identity construction is an ongoing process of development, change and maintenance of identifying with the self.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Research has shown that adolescence is a time of identity progression rather than regression.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] One's identity tends to lack stability in the beginning years of life but gains a more stable sense in later periods of childhood and adolescence.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Typically associated with a time of experimentation, there are endless factors that go into the construction of one's identity.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] As well as being many factors, there are many types of identities one can associate with.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Some categories of identity include gender, sexuality, class, racial and religious, etc.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] For transracial and international adoptees, tension is generally found in the categories of racial, ethnic and national identification.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Because of this, the strength and functionality of family relationships play a huge role in its development and outcome of identity construction.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Transracial and transnational adoptees tend to develop feelings of a lack of acceptance because of such racial, ethnic, and cultural differences.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Therefore, exposing transracial and transnational adoptees to their "cultures of origin" is important in order to better develop a sense of identity and appreciation for cultural diversity.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Identity construction and reconstruction for transnational adoptees the instant they are adopted.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] For example, based upon specific laws and regulations of the United States, the Child Citizen Act of 2000 makes sure to grant immediate U.S. citizenship to adoptees.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Identity is defined both by what one is and what one is not.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adoptees born into one family lose an identity and then borrow one from the adopting family.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The formation of identity is a complicated process and there are many factors that affect its outcome.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] From a perspective of looking at issues in adoption circumstances, the people involved and affected by adoption (the biological parent, the adoptive parent and the adoptee) can be known as the "triad members and state".
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adoption may threaten triad members' sense of identity.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Triad members often express feelings related to confused identity and identity crises because of differences between the triad relationships.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adoption, for some, precludes a complete or integrated sense of self.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Triad members may experience themselves as incomplete, deficient, or unfinished.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] They state that they lack feelings of well-being, integration, or solidity associated with a fully developed identity.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Family plays a vital role in identity formation.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] This is not only true in childhood but also in adolescence.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Identity (gender/sexual/ethnic/religious/family) is still forming during adolescence and family holds a vital key to this.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The research seems to be unanimous; a stable, secure, loving, honest and supportive family in which all members feel safe to explore their identity is necessary for the formation of a sound identity.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Transracial and International adoptions are some factors that play a significant role in the identity construction of adoptees.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Many tensions arise from relationships built between the adoptee(s) and their family.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] These include being "different" from the parent(s), developing a positive racial identity, and dealing with racial/ethnic discrimination.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] These tensions also tend to create questions for the adoptee, as well as the family, to contemplate.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Some common questions include what will happen if the family is more naïve to the ways of socially constructed life?
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Will tensions arise if this is the case?
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] What if the very people that are supposed to be modeling a sound identity are in fact riddled with insecurities?
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Ginni Snodgrass answers these questions in the following way.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The secrecy in an adoptive family and the denial that the adoptive family is different builds dysfunction into it.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] "... social workers and insecure adoptive parents have structured a family relationship that is based on dishonesty, evasions and exploitation.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] To believe that good relationships will develop on such a foundation is psychologically unsound" (Lawrence).
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Secrecy erects barriers to forming a healthy identity.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The research says that the dysfunction, untruths and evasiveness that can be present in adoptive families not only makes identity formation impossible, but also directly works against it.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] What effect on identity formation is present if the adoptee knows they are adopted but has no information about their biological parents?
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adolescent adoptees are overrepresented among those who join sub-cultures, run away, become pregnant, or totally reject their families.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The adoptee population does, however, seem to be more at risk for certain behavioral issues.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Researchers from the University of Minnesota studied adolescents who had been adopted and found that adoptees were twice as likely as non-adopted people to develop oppositional defiant disorder (ODD) and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), with an 8% rate in the general population.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Suicide risks were also significantly greater than the general population.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Swedish researchers found both international and domestic adoptees undertook suicide at much higher rates than non-adopted peers; with international adoptees and female international adoptees, in particular, at highest risk.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Nevertheless, work on adult adoptees has found that the additional risks faced by adoptees are largely confined to adolescence.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Young adult adoptees were shown to be alike with adults from biological families and scored better than adults raised in alternative family types including single parent and step-families.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Moreover, while adult adoptees showed more variability than their non-adopted peers on a range of psychosocial measures, adult adoptees exhibited more similarities than differences with adults who had not been adopted.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] There have been many cases of remediation or the reversibility of early trauma.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] For example, in one of the earliest studies conducted, Professor Goldfarb in England concluded that some children adjust well socially and emotionally despite their negative experiences of institutional deprivation in early childhood.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Other researchers also found that prolonged institutionalization does not necessarily lead to emotional problems or character defects in all children.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] This suggests that there will always be some children who fare well, who are resilient, regardless of their experiences in early childhood.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Furthermore, much of the research on psychological outcomes for adoptees draws from clinical populations.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] This suggests that conclusions such that adoptees are more likely to have behavioral problems such as ODD and ADHD may be biased.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Since the proportion of adoptees that seek mental health treatment is small, psychological outcomes for adoptees compared to those for the general population are more similar than some researchers propose.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] While adoption studies have shown that by adulthood the personalities of adopted siblings are little or no more similar than random pairs of strangers, the parenting style of adoptive parents may still play a role in the outcome of their adoptive children.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Research has suggested that adoptive parents can have impacts on adoptees as well, several recent studies have shown that warm adoptive parenting can reduce behavioral problems of adopted children over time.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adopted children are more likely to experience psychological and behavioral problems than non-adopted peers.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Children who were older than four at the time of their adoption experience more psychological problems than those who were younger.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] According to study in the UK, adopted children can have mental health problems that do not improve even four years after their adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Children with multiple adverse childhood experiences are more likely to have mental health problems.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The study suggests that to identify and treat mental health problems early, care professionals and the adopting parents need detailed biographical information about the child's life.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Another study in the UK suggests that adopted children are more likely to suffer from post-traumatic stress (PTS) than the general population.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Their PTS symptoms depend on the type of adverse experiences they went through and knowledge of their history offers an option for tailored support.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] There is evidence that shows the adoptees of LGBT families and those in heterosexual families have no significant differences in development.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] One of the main arguments used against same-sex adoption is that a child needs a mother and a father in the home to develop properly.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Along with this, a 2009 study showed again that sexual orientation of parents does not affect externalizing and internalized problems, but family functioning and income can affect adjustment, especially for older adoptees.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] "Late-discovery adoption" is a term used to describe the situation where an adopted individual first discovers that they are adopted at a later age than is universally considered to be appropriate, often well into adulthood.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adopted individuals who discover their adoption status at a later age are referred to as late-discovery adoptees (LDAs).
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Failure of the adoptive parent(s) to disclose adoption status to a child is an outdated adoption practice that was once fairly common for adoptees born in the 1930s, 1940s and 1950s.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Since the 1970s, it has been socially unacceptable to keep the truth from adopted individuals regarding their genetic origins.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In Western culture, many see the common image of a family as being that of a heterosexual couple with biological children.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] This idea places alternative family forms outside the norm.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] As a consequence – research indicates – disparaging views of adoptive families exist, along with doubts concerning the strength of their family bonds.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The most recent adoption attitudes survey completed by the Evan Donaldson Institute provides further evidence of this stigma.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Nearly one-third of the surveyed population believed adoptees are less-well adjusted, more prone to medical issues, and predisposed to drug and alcohol problems.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Additionally, 40–45% thought adoptees were more likely to have behavior problems and trouble at school.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In contrast, the same study indicated adoptive parents were viewed favorably, with nearly 90% describing them as "lucky, advantaged, and unselfish".
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The majority of people state that their primary source of information about adoption comes from friends and family and the news media.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Nevertheless, most people report the media provides them a favorable view of adoption; 72% indicated receiving positive impressions.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] There is, however, still substantial criticism of the media's adoption coverage.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Some adoption blogs, for example, criticized *Meet the Robinsons* for using outdated orphanage imagery as did advocacy non-profit The Evan B.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The stigmas associated with adoption are amplified for children in foster care.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Negative perceptions result in the belief that such children are so troubled it would be impossible to adopt them and create "normal" families.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Attitude toward Adoption Questionnaire (ATAQ): this questionnaire was first developed by Abdollahzadeh, Chaloyi and Mahmoudi (2019).
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Preliminary Edition: This questionnaire has 23 items based on the Likert scale of 1 (totally Disagree), up to 5 (Totally Agree) being obtained after refining the items designed to construct the present tool and per-study study.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The analysis of item and initial psychometric analyses indicate that there are two factors in it.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The results of exploratory factor analysis by main components with varimax rotation indicated two components of attitude toward adoption being named respectively cognitive as the aspects of attitude toward adoption and behavioral-emotional aspects of attitude toward adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] These two components explained 43.25% of the variance of the total sample.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Cronbach's alpha coefficient was used to measure the reliability of the questionnaire.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Cronbach's alpha coefficient was 0.709 for the whole questionnaire, 0.71 for the first component, and 0.713 for the second one.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In addition, there was a significant positive relationship between desired social tendencies and the cognitive aspect of attitude toward adoption as well as the behavioral -emotional aspects of attitude toward adoption (P ≤ 0.01).
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Family preservation is the emphasis that, if possible, mothers and children should be kept together.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In the U.S., this was clearly illustrated by the shift in policy of the New York Foundling Home, an adoption-institution that is among the country's oldest and one that had pioneered sealed records.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] It established three new principles including "to prevent placements of children...", reflecting the belief that children would be better served by staying with their biological families, a striking shift in policy that remains in force today.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In addition, groups such as Origins USA (founded in 1997) started to actively speak about family preservation and the rights of mothers.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The intellectual tone of these reform movements was influenced by the publishing of *The Primal Wound* by Nancy Verrier.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] "Primal wound" is described as the "devastation which the infant feels because of separation from its birth mother.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Forced adoption has also been enforced with the rationale of child welfare.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The children of unwed or single mothers are commonly the target of such forced adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] This was prominent during baby scoop era in the 1950s through the 1970s in the anglosphere.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The children of parents in poverty have also been targeted for forced adoption under the rationale of child welfare.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] This was often the case for Verdingkinder or "contract children" in Switzerland between the 1850s through the middle of the twentieth century.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Removing children of ethnic minorities from their families to be adopted by those of the dominant ethnic group has been used as a method of forced assimilation.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Forced adoption based on ethnicity occurred during World War II.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In German-occupied Poland, it is estimated that 200,000 Polish children with purportedly Aryan traits were removed from their families and given to German or Austrian couples, and only 25,000 returned to their families after the war.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The Stolen Generation of Aboriginal people in Australia were affected by similar policies, as were Native Americans in the United States and First Nations of Canada.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] These practices have become significant social and political issues in recent years, and in many cases the policies have changed.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The United States, for example, now has the 1978 Indian Child Welfare Act, which allows the tribe and family of a Native American child to be involved in adoption decisions, with preference being given to adoption within the child's tribe.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] While forced assimilation usually revolves around ethnicity, assimilating children of political minorities has also occurred.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In Spain under Francisco Franco's 1939–1975 dictatorship the newborns of some left-wing opponents of the regime, or unmarried or poor couples, were removed from their mothers and adopted.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] New mothers were frequently told their babies had died suddenly after birth and the hospital had taken care of their burials, when in fact they were given or sold to another family.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] It is believed that up to 300,000 babies were involved.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] These practices—which allegedly involved doctors, nurses, nuns and priests—outlived Franco's death in 1975 and carried on as an illegal baby trafficking network until 1987 when a new law regulating adoption was introduced.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adoption is usually managed by judges, bureaucrats and social workers.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Profiting from giving or receiving orphans has incentivized abusive practices.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Baby farming is the practice of accepting custody of a child in return for payment.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] This was most common in Victorian Britain.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Illegitimacy and its attendant social stigma were usually the impetus for a mother's decision to give her child to a baby farmer.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Baby 'farmers' would sometimes neglect or murder the babies to keep costs down.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Child harvesting is the practice of rearing human children to be sold, typically for adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Poor mothers have used street clinics, known as "baby factories", to deliver babies to be adopted by richer women for payment.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] While this can be voluntary, baby factories have also coerced or abducted women into such facilities to be raped in order to sell their babies for adoption.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Organized rings in Nairobi are known to abduct the children of homeless mothers sleeping on the street.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] During the One Child Policy in China, when women were only allowed to have one child, local governments would often allow the woman to give birth and then they would take the baby away.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Child traffickers, often paid by the government, would sell the children to orphanages that would arrange international adoptions worth tens of thousands of dollars, turning a profit for the government.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adoption practices have changed significantly over the course of the 20th century, with each new movement labeled, in some way, as reform.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Beginning in the 1970s, efforts to improve adoption became associated with opening records and encouraging family preservation.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] These ideas arose from suggestions that the secrecy inherent in modern adoption may influence the process of forming an identity, create confusion regarding genealogy, and provide little in the way of medical history.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Adopted people have long sought to undo these laws so that they can obtain their own original birth certificates.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Movements to unseal original birth certificates and other adoption records for adopted people proliferated in the 1970s along with increased acceptance of illegitimacy.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In the United States, Jean Paton founded Orphan Voyage in 1954, and Florence Fisher founded the Adoptees' Liberty Movement Association (ALMA) in 1971, calling sealed records "an affront to human dignity".
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] While in 1975, Emma May Vilardi created the first mutual-consent registry, the International Soundex Reunion Registry (ISRR), allowing those separated by adoption to locate one another. and Lee Campbell and other birthmothers established CUB (Concerned United Birthparents).
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Similar ideas were taking hold globally with grass-roots organizations like Parent Finders in Canada and Jigsaw in Australia.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In 1975, England and Wales opened records on moral grounds.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] A coalition of New York and national adoptee rights activists successfully worked to overturn a restrictive 83-year-old law in 2019, and adult adopted people born in New York, as well as their descendants, today have the right to request and obtain their own original birth certificates.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In 2024, Minnesota became the fifteenth state to ensure adopted people have the legal right to obtain their original birth certificate.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In 2025, Georgia enacted a law that restored the right to adult adopted people to request their own original birth records, becoming the sixteenth state in the United States to do so.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Since the 1970s, changes in social attitudes have resulted in examination of the language used in adoption and shifts in language use.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Controversies in adoption reform efforts have been reflected in the varying terminology recommended by adoptive parents, birth parents, adoptees, and professionals involved in the adoption process such as social workers.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Two of the contrasting sets of terms are commonly referred to as "positive adoption language" (PAL, sometimes called "respectful adoption language" or RAL), and "honest adoption language".
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] As adoption search and support organizations developed, there were challenges to the language in common use at the time.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In contrast, proponents of "honest adoption language" (HAL) emphasize the value of the family relationships that existed prior to legal adoption and note that mothers who have "voluntarily surrendered" children seldom view it as a choice that was freely made.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Proponents of "honest language adoption" argue that the use of the term "birth mother" dehumanizes women who have given birth, likening them to an incubator, and does not reflect that mother-child relationships continue after the physical act of giving birth.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Estimates for the extent of search behavior by adoptees have proven elusive; studies show significant variation.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In part, the problem stems from the small adoptee population which makes random surveying difficult, if not impossible.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Nevertheless, some indication of the level of search interest by adoptees can be gleaned from the case of England and Wales which opened adoptees' birth records in 1975.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Office for National Statistics has projected that 33% of all adoptees would eventually request a copy of their original birth records, exceeding original forecasts made in 1975 when it was believed that only a small fraction of the adoptee population would request their records.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The projection is known to underestimate the true search rate, however, since many adoptees of the era get their birth records by other means.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] It is speculated by adoption researchers, however, that the reasons given are incomplete: although such information could be communicated by a third-party, interviews with adoptees, who sought reunion, found they expressed a need to actually meet biological relations.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] It appears the desire for reunion is linked to the adoptee's interaction with and acceptance within the community.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Internally focused theories suggest some adoptees possess ambiguities in their sense of self, impairing their ability to present a consistent identity.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Reunion helps resolve the lack of self-knowledge.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Externally focused theories, in contrast, suggest that reunion is a way for adoptees to overcome social stigma.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] The externally focused rationale for reunion suggests adoptees may be well adjusted and happy within their adoptive families, but will search as an attempt to resolve experiences of social stigma.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Some adoptees reject the idea of reunion.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] It is unclear, though, what differentiates adoptees who search from those who do not.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In sum, reunions can bring a variety of issues for adoptees and parents.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Nevertheless, most reunion results appear to be positive.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In the largest study to date (based on the responses of 1,007 adoptees and relinquishing parents), 90% responded that reunion was a beneficial experience.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] This does not, however, imply ongoing relationships were formed between adoptee and parent nor that this was the goal.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Attitudes and laws regarding adoption vary greatly.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Whereas all cultures make arrangements whereby children whose birth parents are unavailable to rear them can be brought up by others, not all cultures have the concept of adoption, that is treating unrelated children as equivalent to biological children of the adoptive parents.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] Under Islamic Law, for example, adopted children must keep their original surname to be identified with blood relations, and, traditionally, women wear a hijab in the presence of males in their adoptive households.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In Egypt, these cultural distinctions have led to making adoption illegal opting instead for a system of foster care.
[src:antinatalism/adopt-p02] In some countries, such as the United States, "Homecoming Day" is the day when an adoptee is officially united with their new adoptive family.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic properties are features that influence the appeal of objects.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They include aesthetic values, which express positive or negative qualities, such as the contrast between beauty and ugliness.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Philosophers debate whether aesthetic properties have objective existence or depend on the subjective experiences of observers.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] According to a common view, aesthetic experiences are associated with disinterested pleasure detached from practical concerns.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Taste is a subjective sensitivity to aesthetic qualities, and differences in taste can lead to disagreements about aesthetic judgments.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Artworks are artifacts or performances typically created by humans, encompassing diverse forms such as painting, music, dance, architecture, and literature.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Some definitions focus on their intrinsic aesthetic qualities; others understand art as a socially constructed category.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Art interpretation and criticism seek to identify the meanings of artworks.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Discussions focus on elements such as what an artwork represents, which emotions it expresses, and what the author's underlying intent was.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Many fields of study investigate aesthetic phenomena, examining their roles in ethics, religion, and everyday life, as well as the psychological processes involved in aesthetic experiences.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Comparative aesthetics analyzes the similarities and differences between traditions such as Western, Indian, Chinese, Islamic, and African aesthetics.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic thought has its roots in antiquity but only emerged as a distinct field of inquiry in the 18th century when philosophers systematically engaged with the subject.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetics, sometimes spelled *esthetics*, is the systematic study of beauty, art, and taste.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] As a branch of philosophy, it examines which types of aesthetic phenomena there are, how people experience them, and how objects evoke them.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This field also investigates the nature of aesthetic judgments, the meaning of artworks, and the problem of art criticism.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Key questions in aesthetics include "What is art?", "Can aesthetic judgments be objective?", and "How is aesthetic value related to other values?".
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One characterization distinguishes between three main approaches to aesthetics: the study of aesthetic concepts and judgments, the study of aesthetic experiences and other mental responses, and the study of the nature and features of aesthetic objects.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] In a slightly different sense, the term *aesthetics* can also refer to particular theories of beauty or to beautiful appearances.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetics is closely related to the philosophy of art, and the two terms are often used interchangeably since both involve the philosophical study of aesthetic phenomena.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One difference is that the philosophy of art focuses on art, whereas the scope of aesthetics also includes other domains, such as beauty in nature and everyday life.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Accordingly, one outlook argues that the philosophy of art is a subfield of aesthetics.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The precise relation between the two fields is disputed, and another characterization holds that the philosophy of art is the broader discipline.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This view asserts that aesthetics mainly addresses aesthetic properties, while the philosophy of art also investigates non-aesthetic features of artworks, belonging to fields such as metaphysics, epistemology, philosophy of language, and ethics.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Even though the philosophical study of aesthetic problems originated in antiquity, it was not until the 18th century that aesthetics emerged as a distinct branch of philosophy when philosophers engaged in systematic inquiry into its principles.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The Latin term *aesthetica* was coined by the philosopher Alexander Baumgarten in 1735, initially defined as the study of sensibility or sensations of beautiful objects.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The term comes from the ancient Greek words *aisthetikos*, meaning 'perceptible things', *aisthesthai*, meaning 'perceive, see', and *aisthesis*, meaning 'sensation, perception'.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The earliest known use in the English language appeared in a translation by W.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Philosophers rely on several basic concepts in their inquiry.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They examine aesthetic objects and the properties or features responsible for their appeal, such as beauty.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Researchers study the experience and pleasure these objects evoke, the judgments about them, and taste as an underlying sensitivity.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] However, this field comes with theoretical difficulties caused by disagreements about the definitions of and relations between these concepts.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Similarly, the exact boundaries of the domain of aesthetics as a whole are disputed—it is controversial whether there is a group of essential features shared by all aesthetic phenomena or whether they are more loosely related through family resemblances.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic properties are features of an object that shape its appeal or factors that influence aesthetic evaluations.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For instance, when an art critic describes an artwork as *great*, *vivid*, or *amusing*, they express aesthetic properties of this artwork.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Some aesthetic properties focus on aesthetic value in general, like *beautiful* and *ugly*; others center on more specific forms of value, such as *graceful* and *elegant*.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic properties can also refer to perceptual qualities of objects like *balanced* and *vivid*, to representational aspects like *realistic* and *distorted*, or to emotional responses such as *joyful* and *angry*.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The precise distinction between aesthetic and non-aesthetic properties is disputed.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] According to one proposal, aesthetic properties require a specific aesthetic sensitivity in addition to the sensory perception of non-aesthetic properties, going beyond simple colors, shapes, and sounds.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic properties are associated with evaluations, but not all are intrinsically good or bad.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For example, being a realistic representation may be aesthetically good in some artistic contexts and bad in others.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The school of realism argues that aesthetic properties are objective, mind-independent features of reality.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A related proposal asserts that they are emergent properties dependent on non-aesthetic properties.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] According to this view, the beauty of a painting may emerge from the right combination of colors and shapes.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A different position holds that aesthetic properties are response-dependent, for example, that features of objects only qualify as aesthetic properties if they evoke aesthetic experiences in observers.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The terms "aesthetic property" and "aesthetic quality" are often used interchangeably.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Some philosophers distinguish the two, associating aesthetic properties with objective features and aesthetic qualities with subjective experiences and emotional responses.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] An aesthetic object is an object with aesthetic properties.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One interpretation suggests that aesthetic objects are material entities that evoke aesthetic experiences.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] According to this view, if a person admires an oil painting, then the physical canvas and paint make up the aesthetic object.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Another interpretation, associated with the school of phenomenology, argues that aesthetic objects are not material but intentional objects.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Intentional objects are part of the content of experiences, and their existence depends on the perceiver.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] An intentional object may accurately reflect a material object, as in the case of veridical perceptions, but can also fail to do so, which happens during perceptual illusions.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The phenomenological perspective focuses on the intentional object given in experience rather than the material object considered independently of the perceiver.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic values are a special type of aesthetic property.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They express the sensory appeal of an object as a qualitative measure of its aesthetic merit, encompassing both positive and negative evaluations.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic values contrast with values in other domains, such as moral, epistemic, religious, and economic values.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The aesthetic value of beauty is often singled out as a central topic of aesthetics.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It is a key aspect of human experience, influencing both personal decisions and cultural developments.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Often-cited examples of beautiful objects include landscapes, sunsets, humans, and artworks.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] As a positive value, beauty contrasts with ugliness as its negative counterpart.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Beauty is typically understood as a quality of objects that involves balance or harmony and evokes admiration or pleasure when perceived, but its precise definition is debated.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Some theories understand beauty as an objective feature of external objects.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Others emphasize its subjective nature, linking it to personal experience and perception.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They argue that "beauty is in the eye of the beholder" rather than in the perceived object.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Another central debate concerns the features that all beautiful objects have in common.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The so-called *classical conception of beauty* is rooted in classical antiquity and the Italian Renaissance.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Focusing on objective features, it asserts that beauty is a harmonious arrangement of parts into a coherent whole.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic hedonism, by contrast, is a subjective theory holding that a thing is beautiful if it acts as a source of aesthetic pleasure.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Other conceptions define beautiful objects in terms of intrinsic value, the manifestation of ideal forms, or as what evokes love and passion.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] In pre-modern philosophy, beauty was often treated as the only aesthetic value.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This outlook holds that beauty encompasses all that is aesthetically commendable and serves as a unifying concept of the whole domain of aesthetics.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] As discussions of aesthetic phenomena expanded, other aesthetic values were proposed.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For example, the sublime is another value of things that inspire feelings of awe and fear.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Further suggested values include charm, elegance, harmony, and grace.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] An aesthetic experience is an appreciation of beauty or an awareness of other aesthetic features.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] In its most typical form, it is a sensory perception of a natural object or an artwork.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It can also take other forms, such as aesthetic imagination of fictional objects described in literature.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Internalist theories, like Monroe Beardsley's view, explain aesthetic experience from a first-person perspective, focusing on aspects internal to the experience, such as focus and intensity.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] By contrast, externalist theories, such as George Dickie's position, argue that the key element of aesthetic experiences comes from the perceived external objects and their aesthetic properties.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Several features are associated with aesthetic experiences, but it is controversial whether any of them are essential.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic experiences usually appreciate an object for its own sake because of its sensory properties, resulting in aesthetic pleasure from a positive evaluation of the object.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This pleasure is typically said to be detached from practical concerns and can involve selfless absorption, allowing imaginative freedom or free play of mental faculties in addition to sensory perception.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Some theorists associate this free play with an absence of conceptual activity.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic experiences may also be normative, meaning that certain responses are appropriate, like the positive appreciation of beauty, but others are not, such as the positive appreciation of ugliness.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A central aspect of aesthetic experience is the aesthetic attitude—a special way of observing or engaging with art and nature.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This attitude involves a form of pure appreciation of perceptual qualities detached from personal desires and practical concerns.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It is disinterested in this sense by engaging with an object for its own sake without ulterior motives or practical consequences.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For example, the experience of a violent storm through the aesthetic attitude may focus on its intricate patterns of lightning and thunder rather than preparing for its immediate dangers.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One characterization understands the aesthetic attitude as a natural form of apprehension that occurs on its own in certain situations.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Another outlook holds that the aesthetic attitude is a voluntary stance people can choose to adopt toward any object.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] There is debate about the extent and type of emotional engagement a disinterested stance requires, for instance, whether fear during a horror movie can be disinterested.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The aesthetic attitude is sometimes contrasted with other attitudes, such as the practical attitude, which is interested in usefulness and seeks to utilize or manipulate objects to achieve specific goals.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Similarly, it differs from the scientific attitude, which aims to explain phenomena and acquire factual knowledge about the world.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Some philosophers, such as Arthur Schopenhauer and Martin Heidegger, suggest that the aesthetic attitude can reveal aspects of reality obscured in other attitudes.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic experience is further associated with aesthetic pleasure—a form of enjoyment in response to natural and artistic beauty.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It is typically characterized as disinterested pleasure.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It contrasts with interested pleasure that arises from the satisfaction of desires, such as the joy of achieving a personal goal or indulging in a particular type of food one craves.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Another difference is that aesthetic pleasure does not depend on the existence of the enjoyed object, like enjoying the beauty of a sunset in a dream.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The joy in achieving a personal goal, by contrast, would be frustrated if one discovered that the achievement was merely a dream.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Philosophers like Immanuel Kant argue that aesthetic pleasure is preconceptual, meaning that it arises from a free interplay between imagination and understanding rather than from cognitive judgments or conceptual analysis.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One view distinguishes refined from unrefined aesthetic pleasures based on whether the pleasure is evoked by a cultivated taste or an immediate, instinctual response.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic pleasure is central to the characterization of many aesthetic phenomena that are said to involve or evoke such pleasure.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] However, the view that aesthetic pleasure is the defining characteristic of the entire aesthetic domain is controversial.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It faces challenges in explaining phenomena such as the sublime, drama, tragedy, and forms of modern art, which may evoke diverse emotions not primarily linked to pleasure.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic judgments are assessments of the aesthetic features and values of objects, expressed in statements like "this music is beautiful".
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They can apply both to natural objects and artworks.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic judgments also include assessments about how or why an object has aesthetic value without explicitly determining its overall aesthetic worth, as in the statement "this music is balanced".
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Many debates in aesthetics concern the nature of aesthetic judgments, in particular, whether they can be as objective and universal as empirical judgments made by natural scientists.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Subjectivists argue that aesthetic judgments express personal feelings and dislikes without universal validity.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This view is contested by objectivists, who hold that aesthetic judgments describe objective features that are independent of the particular preferences of the judging individual.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Intermediate views suggest that the standards of aesthetic judgment are grounded in stable shared dispositions rather than variable individual preferences, resulting in a form of subjective universality.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This position is reflected in Kant's view, which identifies four core features of aesthetic judgments: they are subjective, universal, disinterested, and involve an interplay of sense, imagination, and understanding.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Philosophers such as Francis Hutcheson and David Hume argue that there are general aesthetic principles or universal criteria that are applied when making aesthetic judgments.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Particularists, by contrast, assert that the unique nature of each aesthetic object requires a case-by-case evaluation that cannot be fully subsumed under general principles.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A related debate between rationalism and the immediacy thesis concerns whether aesthetic judgments are mediated through concept application and reasoning or emerge directly from sensory intuition.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic judgments rely on taste, which is a sensitivity to aesthetic qualities, a capacity to feel aesthetic pleasure, or an ability to discern beauty and other aesthetic qualities.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Taste is a type of preference expressed in immediate reactions and is sometimes understood as an inner sense or cognitive faculty.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Differences in taste are often used to explain why people disagree about aesthetic judgments and why the judgments of some people, such as art critics with extensive experience and a refined sense, carry more weight than those of casual observers.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Taste varies both among cultures and among individuals within a culture.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] There are also some cross-cultural agreements.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Several philosophers argue that taste can be learned to some extent and that the judgments of experienced observers follow similar standards, suggesting the existence of social norms of right and wrong aesthetic assessments.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The term "aesthetic universal" refers to aspects of taste and other aesthetic phenomena that are shared across different cultures and societies, indicating common features of human nature underlying aesthetics.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Suggested general tendencies include the dispositions to engage in artistic expressions or to derive aesthetic pleasure from appreciating these expressions.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The existence of more specific shared tendencies is debated.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] An example is the idea that humans generally find savanna-like landscapes with open grassy plains and scattered trees pleasing.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Art is a central topic of aesthetics and the main subject of the philosophy of art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It encompasses diverse forms, including painting, sculpture, music, dance, literature, and theater.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This field covers both artworks and the skills or activities involved in their creation.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Artworks are artifacts or performances typically created by humans.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They differ in this respect from naturally occurring aesthetic objects, like landscapes and sunsets.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A central debate in the philosophy of art concerns the definition of art or how to distinguish it from non-art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] There are many theories, each offering a unique perspective on the nature of art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Essentialist approaches argue that there is an essence or a set of inherent features shared by all artworks and only by them.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They often define artworks in terms of other aesthetic concepts, such as *representation*, *beauty*, or *aesthetic experience*.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] An early object-centered approach, first proposed by Plato, characterizes artworks as representations that seek to reflect or imitate certain aspects of reality.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Another definition suggests that artworks are objects designed to evoke aesthetic experiences or pleasure.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A related approach proposes that all artworks have certain aesthetic properties in common, such as beauty.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aesthetic formalism argues that specific formal features, such as a "significant form", are the hallmark of art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Artist-centered approaches see artistic activity as the essential aspect of artworks.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One conception understands artworks as special vehicles through which artists express emotions and other mental states.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Conventionalist definitions view art as a socially constructed category.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This means that it does not primarily depend on the inherent properties of objects, for example, what they represent or what forms they have.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Instead, art is defined by social and cultural agreements, which are subject to change.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A key motivation for this approach has been the emergence of modern art, which has challenged many earlier conceptions.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Conventionalist definitions can explain, for instance, that even mundane ready-made objects like a urinal are considered art if conventions say so.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Institutional theories argue that the conventions are set by social institutions of the art world.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Because of this social dependence, an object considered art in one society may not be art in another society.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Historical theories, another form of conventionalism, assert that the category of art depends on established traditions and historical contexts.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They claim that an object becomes part of this category if it stands in the right relation to these traditions, for example, by being created in an artistic context and resembling other recognized artworks.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] There are also hybrid theories that combine elements from other theories.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For instance, one approach holds that an object is an artwork if it either meets certain aesthetic standards or is conventionally regarded as art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The diversity of proposed definitions and the difficulties in reconciling them have led some philosophers to argue against the existence of precise criteria.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Some conclude that a definition is strictly impossible.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Others provide vague characterizations, suggesting that the domain of art is characterized by overlapping similarities, known as family resemblance.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The ontology of art seeks to discern the fundamental categories of being to which all artworks belong.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One approach argues that artworks are universals—general or repeatable entities that can have several instances at the same time.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For example, a novel can have many copies, a film can have many screenings, and a photo can have many prints.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One version of this view distinguishes artworks as types from their instances, which are considered tokens of this type.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A different outlook rejects the idea that artworks are universals, arguing instead that they are particulars or unique concrete entities.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For them, if there are several instances, then the artwork is the collection or sum of all instances.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] According to this view, Alfred Stieglitz's photograph *The Steerage* is not a type underlying its prints but rather the collection or sum of all prints together.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A similar discussion addresses whether artworks are material objects, which exist independent of observers, or intentional objects, which exist in the experience of observers.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Pluralists argue that different types of artworks belong to distinct ontological categories.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Contextualists accept this view and further propose that the ontological category depends on the context of discussion.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Deflationism is skeptical about the fundamental existence of artworks in any form.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It acknowledges that the term *art* may be practically useful in everyday language but rejects that it refers to any fundamental entities of reality.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Some distinctions focus on the medium used to express artistic ideas.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For example, paintings typically use paint, such as oil or acrylic paint, which is distributed on a surface, whereas dance involves bodily movements.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Similarly, music is performed using instruments and voice to produce sounds, and literature relies on language.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Hybrid forms like opera and film combine several of these elements.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Another distinction is between performance works and object works.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Performance works, like a song performed on stage, are dynamically enacted in time, whereas object works, like a painting, have a more static nature.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Artworks can also be classified by art historic style, such as impressionism and surrealism, and by their intended purpose, like political and religious art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The meaning of an artwork is what is involved in understanding it or comprehending what it communicates, encompassing factors such as representation and expression.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Certain aspects of meaning may be directly accessible; others require in-depth interpretation, for example, to grasp symbolic or metaphorical elements.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Understanding influences aesthetic experience, and for certain artworks, a comprehensive understanding may be required to fully appreciate them.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One approach to the analysis of meaning is the distinction between form and content.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Content refers to what is presented, such as the depicted topic, expressed ideas, and conceptual messages.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Form refers to how the content is presented, such as medium, technique, composition, and style.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Form encompasses modes of presentation in different art forms, like color and spatial arrangement in painting, harmony and rhythm in music, and narrative voice and plot structure in literature.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Representation is a depiction of real or imagined entities.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For example, a portrait painting represents a person, and a fantasy novel represents an imaginary chain of events.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Similarity is a crucial element in many forms of artistic representation, meaning that the artwork resembles the depicted entity.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Representation can also happen through other means, such as conventional symbols and established codes.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It is particularly prevalent in certain art forms and styles, such as classical art and realism.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Since antiquity, representation has been a key concept in theories of art, such as Plato's idea of defining art as imitation.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] However, it is controversial whether representation plays a central role in all art forms, including music and abstract modern art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Expression is the conveyance of psychological states, such as emotions, moods, and attitudes.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For example, a painter may depict a barren landscape in muted colors to express sadness, and a musician might use a fast tempo and upbeat melody to convey excitement.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The expressed mental states often align with the artist's personal experience.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] However, this is not necessarily the case, and artists may explore psychological states they observed in others or entirely fictional experiences.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] An artwork can express a mental state like sadness by evoking it in the experience of the audience.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Alternatively, the expression can also happen if observers recognize the presence of sadness in the artwork even if they do not personally feel it.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Expression theories consider expression a core feature of artworks.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They characterize artworks as expressions of the artist's mind, focusing on creativity and originality in the manifestation of aesthetic experiences.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The process of interpretation is the attempt to uncover the meaning of an artwork to understand its significance and value.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] In the widest sense, interpretation encompasses any way of assigning meaning, including obvious descriptions of depicted entities and explanations of literal word meanings.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Interpretations aim to discover underlying aspects that are relevant to the understanding and appreciation of the artwork.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The terms *interpretation* and *criticism* are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] However, criticism is typically associated with more components, like a general description of the criticized artwork and a classification of style and genre.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Criticism also explains the art-historical background and evaluates positive and negative qualities.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Critics sometimes propose conflicting interpretations of the same artwork.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] According to critical monism, there is only one comprehensive correct interpretation, implying that conflicting interpretations cannot both be correct.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Critical pluralism, by contrast, asserts that there can be different but equally valid interpretations and that it is not always possible to determine which of two conflicting interpretations is superior.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] A similar debate addresses whether interpretations can be true or false in an objective sense.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Several frameworks of interpretation have been proposed.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] According to intentionalism, the meaning of an artwork is determined by the author's intent—their reasons and motives that led to the creation of the artwork.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This typically involves analyzing the ideas the artist aimed to express but can also include a biographical analysis to learn about psychological and social circumstances in the artist's life.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Intentionalism is a controversial theory, termed the *intentional fallacy* by its critics.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Some objections point to cases where the author's intention cannot be known, where the author cannot be identified, or where no traditional author exists, as in artworks created by artificial intelligence.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] In these cases, meaning would be inaccessible or non-existent.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Other objections assert that an artist may fail to accurately express their intention or may manifest unintended aesthetic features, suggesting that an artwork can contain both less and more than the artist intended.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] An alternative to intentionalism argues that meaning is determined by artistic, stylistic, linguistic, and other cultural conventions.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] For example, linguistic conventions determine the literal meanings of words and thereby influence the overall meaning of a poem.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Another framework holds that meaning is shaped by how the audience, rather than the author, interprets or would interpret the intention underlying the work.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Artistic formalism proposes a different approach by focusing interpretation exclusively on formal or perceptual features of artworks.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aestheticism and instrumentalism are theories about the value of art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Aestheticism asserts that the primary value of art lies in its intrinsic aesthetic merits, independent of any external purposes.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] This idea of the autonomy of art is expressed in the slogan "art for art's sake".
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Strong forms of aestheticism not only disregard external purposes but see them as detrimental influences that undermine artistic integrity.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Instrumentalism, by contrast, explains the value of art by the effects it has on other domains.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It understands art as a means to things such as moral education, spiritual growth, therapeutic benefits, and social cohesion.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The individual arts are practices or disciplines in the domain of art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] They encompass a wide range of fields, including traditionally established forms such as painting, music, and literature, as well as newer types like video games.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] One classification divides them into visual arts, literary arts, and performance arts.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The boundaries between these categories are not always clear, and alternative classifications have been proposed.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] Painting is a visual art in which a painter applies colors to a surface.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] It allows for a diverse range of motives and styles, and is often considered a paradigm form of art.
[src:antinatalism/aesthetic-p01] The representation of real entities plays a central role in many forms of painting, ranging from landscapes and people to historic events.
